    "question_id" : 3674930,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<p>If you want the dot or other characters with a special meaning in regexes to be a normal character, you have to escape it with a backslash. Since regexes in Java are normal Java strings, you need to escape the backslash itself, so you need two backslashes e.g. <code>\\\\.</code> </p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 10843,
      "reputation" : 337423,
      "user_id" : 20670,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 100,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/251f2449ffba9fbcc3491db6564ff4a2?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Tim Pietzcker",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/20670/tim-pietzcker"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 21,
    "last_activity_date" : 1383309342,
    "last_edit_date" : 1383309342,
    "creation_date" : 1284022331,
    "answer_id" : 3675086,
    "question_id" : 3674930,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Perl-style regular expressions (which the Java regex engine is more or less based upon) treat the following characters as special characters:</p>\n\n<p><code>.^$|*+?()[{\\</code> have special meaning <em>outside</em> of character classes,</p>\n\n<p><code>]^-\\</code> have special meaning <em>inside</em> of character classes (<code>[...]</code>).</p>\n\n<p>So you need to escape those (and only those) symbols depending on context (or, in the case of character classes, place them in positions where they can't be misinterpreted). </p>\n\n<p>Needlessly escaping other characters  may work, but some regex engines will treat this as syntax errors, for example <code>\\_</code> will cause an error in .NET.</p>\n\n<p>Some others will lead to false results, for example <code>\\&lt;</code> is interpreted as a literal <code>&lt;</code> in Perl, but in <code>egrep</code> it means \"word boundary\".</p>\n\n<p>So write <code>-?\\d+\\.\\d+\\$</code> to match <code>1.50$</code>, <code>-2.00$</code> etc. and <code>[(){}[\\]]</code> for a character class that matches all kinds of brackets/braces/parentheses.</p>\n\n<p>If you need to transform a user input string into a regex-safe form, use <code>java.util.regex.Pattern.quote</code>.</p>\n\n<p>Further reading: <a href=\"http://www.regexguru.com/2008/12/dont-escape-literal-characters-that-arent-metacharacters/\" rel=\"noreferrer\">Jan Goyvaert's blog RegexGuru on escaping metacharacters</a></p>\n"
  }, {
